{"title_page": "Vidyagauri Nilkanth", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=July 2018}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name        = Vidyagauri Nilkanth\n|image       = Vidyaben Nilkanth 1895.jpg\n|image_size  = 180px\n|caption     = Vidyagauri around 1895\n|birth_date  = {{Birth date|df=yes|1876|6|1}} \n|birth_place = [[Ahmedabad]]\n|death_date  = {{death date and age|df=yes|1958|12|07|1876|6|1}} \n|death_place = \n|other_names = \n|spouse      = {{marriage|[[Ramanbhai Nilkanth]]|1889}}\n|children    = [[Vinodini Nilkanth]], [[Sarojini Mehta]] (daughters)\n|known_for   = [[Social reformer]], educationist and writer\n|awards      =\n|relatives = [[Sharda Mehta]] (sister)\n}}\n\n'''Vidyagauri Nilkanth''' was an Indian social reformer, educationist, and writer. She was also one of the first two women graduates in [[Gujarat]].<ref name=\"Stree Shakti\">{{cite web|title=Stree Shakti|url=http://www.streeshakti.com/bookV.aspx?author=3|accessdate=2016-11-10}}</ref><ref name=\"Win Entrance Biography\">{{cite web|title=Win Entrance Biography|url=http://www.winentrance.com/general_knowledge/vidya-gauri-nilkanth.html|accessdate=2016-11-10}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\n[[File:Ramanbhai Nilkanth Vidyagauri Nilkanth.jpg|thumb|Vidyagauri with her husband [[Ramanbhai Nilkanth]]|upright=0.8|left]]\nVidyagauri Nilkanth was born on 1 June 1876 in [[Ahmedabad]]. She was the daughter of a judicial officer, Gopilal Dhruva and Balaben.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://gujaratisahityaparishad.com/prakashan/sarjako/savishesh/Savishesh-Vidyagauri-Nilkanth.html|title=\u0ab5\u0abf\u0aa6\u0acd\u0aaf\u0abe\u0a97\u0acc\u0ab0\u0ac0 \u0aa8\u0ac0\u0ab2\u0a95\u0a82\u0aa0|last=Bhatt|first=Pushpa|website=gujaratisahityaparishad.com|publisher=[[Gujarati Sahitya Parishad]]|language=gu|trans-title=Vidyagauri Nilkanth|access-date=2019-01-21}}</ref><ref name=\"Stree Shakti\"/> She was a granddaughter of [[Bholanath Divetia]], a social reformer and poet.<ref name=\":2\">{{cite journal|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DeaVBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA17|title=International Journal of Afro-Asian Studies|last=Sujata|first=Menon|publisher=Universal-Publishers|year=2013|isbn=978-1-61233-709-8|editor-last=Sarkar|editor-first=Siddhartha|volume=4|location=|pages=17\u201318|issue=1}}</ref> She got her primary education (till Class VII) from Raibahadur Maganbhai Girl's High School and completed secondary school education from Anglo-vernacular classes at the Mahalakshmi Teachers Training College. She married [[Ramanbhai Nilkanth]] in 1889 and together they wrote many articles, books and jointly edited a magazine, ''Jnansudha''.<ref name=\"Win Entrance Biography\"/><ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":2\" /> [[Vinodini Nilkanth]] and [[Sarojini Mehta]] were their daughters.<ref name=\":1\"/>\n\nWith the support of her husband, she completed her matriculation in 1891 standing the first in Gujarati in the [[University of Mumbai|University of Bombay]] and pursued higher education.<ref name=\":2\" /> She enrolled in 1894 and graduated from [[Gujarat College]] with a [[Bachelor of Arts]] in moral philosophy and logic in 1901. Her education was interrupted by frequent pregnancies.<ref name=\":2\" /> She was awarded a fellowship and thus her younger sister, [[Sharda Mehta]], and she became the first two women graduates in Gujarat.<ref name=\"Win Entrance Biography\"/><ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/70200087|title=\u0ab5\u0ac0\u0ab8\u0aae\u0ac0 \u0ab8\u0aa6\u0ac0\u0aa8\u0ac1\u0a82 \u0a97\u0ac1\u0a9c\u0ab0\u0abe\u0aa4\u0ac0 \u0aa8\u0abe\u0ab0\u0ac0\u0ab2\u0ac7\u0a96\u0aa8|last=|first=|publisher=[[Sahitya Akademi]]|others=|year=2005|isbn=8126020350|editor-last=Chaudhari|editor-first=Raghuveer|editor-link=Raghuveer Chaudhari|edition=1st|location=New Delhi|pages=349, 351|language=gu|trans-title=20 Century Women's Writing's in Gujarati|chapter=\u0ab2\u0ac7\u0a96\u0abf\u0a95\u0abe-\u0aaa\u0ab0\u0abf\u0a9a\u0aaf|trans-chapter=Introduction of Women Writers|oclc=70200087|editor-last2=Dalal|editor-first2=Anila|editor-link2=Anila Dalal}}</ref>\n\n==Social work==\nNilkanth was involved social work from a young age. She devoted her life for the upliftment of women.<ref name=\"Win Entrance Biography\"/> She started tailoring classes for poor Muslim women with support from the [[National Indian Association]]. She organized adult education classes and various activities for the War Relief Fund during [[World War I]]. She was made [[Order of the British Empire|MBE]] for her service. She started the Ahmedabad branch of the [[All India Women's Conference]]. She also presided over the Lucknow session of the AIWC. She was associated with numerous educational institutions such as the Maganbhai Karamchand Girls\u2019 High School, the Diwalibai Girls\u2019 School, Ranchhodhal Chhotalal Girls\u2019 High School and the Vanita Vishrams which provided secondary education to women who were widows or dropouts from school because of marriage.<ref name=\"Stree Shakti\"/>\n\nShe founded Lalshanker Umia Shanker Mahila Pathshala, which was later affiliated to [[SNDT Women's University|SNDT (Karve) University]]. She taught English, Psychology and Philosophy in this college.<ref name=\"Stree Shakti\"/>\n\nShe was briefly served as a government appointed  member of a committee in the [[Amdavad Municipal Corporation|Ahmedabad municipality]].<ref name=\":0\" /> She was associated with Prartha Samaj and was Honorary Secretary and then President of the Mahipatram Rupram Anath Ashram, an orphanage.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\"Stree Shakti\"/>\n\n== Literary career ==\nShe contributed to women\u2019s magazines such as ''Gunsundari'', ''Streebodh'', and ''Sharada''. She was the president of the 15th session of the [[Gujarati Sahitya Parishad]]. She had also served as a president of [[Gujarat Vidhya Sabha|Gujarat Vidya Sabha]] and [[Gujarat Sahitya Sabha]].<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\"Stree Shakti\"/><ref name=\":1\" />\n\nShe had written several essays with light humour as well as biographical sketches. ''Foram'' (1955) includes biographical sketches of his relatives and associates which influenced her. He other essay collections are: ''Grihadipika'' (1931), ''Narikunj'' (1956), ''Gyansudha'' (1957). Her miscellaneous essays are included in ''Hasyamandir''. She had written biography ''Pro. Dhondo Keshav Karve'' (1916).<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" />\n\nWith her sister [[Sharda Mehta]], she translated [[R.C. Dutt|Romesh Chunder Dutt]]\u2019s book, ''[[The Lake of Palms]]'' (1902) as Sudhasuhasini (1907); and [[Baroda State|The Maharani of Baroda]] (Chimnabai II)'s ''Position of Women in Indian Life'' (1911) as ''Hindustanma Streeonu Samajik Sthan'' (1915).<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\"Stree Shakti\"/>\n\n== Awards ==\nIn 1926, she was awarded [[Kaisar-i-Hind Medal|Kaisar-i-Hind]] medal.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[List of Gujarati-language writers]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nilkanth, Vidyagauri}}\n[[Category:1876 births]]\n[[Category:1958 deaths]]\n[[Category:Women writers from Gujarat]]\n[[Category:19th-century Indian women writers]]\n[[Category:19th-century Indian writers]]\n[[Category:Indian social reformers]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian women writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian writers]]\n[[Category:Writers from Ahmedabad]]\n[[Category:Indian women activists]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Kaisar-i-Hind Medal]]\n[[Category:University of Mumbai alumni]]\n[[Category:Indian essayists]]\n[[Category:Indian biographers]]\n[[Category:Indian women non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Indian translators]]\n[[Category:Indian social workers]]\n[[Category:Nilkanth family]]\n[[Category:19th-century translators]]\n[[Category:Women biographers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=July 2018}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name        = Vidyagauri Nilkanth\n|image       = Vidyaben Nilkanth 1895.jpg\n|image_size  = 180px\n|caption     = Vidyagauri around 1895\n|birth_date  = {{Birth date|df=yes|1876|6|1}} \n|birth_place = [[Ahmedabad]]\n|death_date  = {{death date and age|df=yes|1958|12|07|1876|6|1}} \n|death_place = \n|other_names = \n|spouse      = {{marriage|[[Ramanbhai Nilkanth]]|1889}}\n|children    = [[Vinodini Nilkanth]], [[Sarojini Mehta]] (daughters)\n|known_for   = [[Social reformer]], educationist and writer\n|awards      =\n|relatives = [[Sharda Mehta]] (sister)\n}}\n\n'''Vidyagauri Nilkanth''' was an Indian social reformer, educationist, and writer. She was also one of the first two women graduates in [[Gujarat]].<ref name=\"Stree Shakti\">{{cite web|title=Stree Shakti|url=http://www.streeshakti.com/bookV.aspx?author=3|accessdate=2016-11-10}}</ref><ref name=\"Win Entrance Biography\">{{cite web|title=Win Entrance Biography|url=http://www.winentrance.com/general_knowledge/vidya-gauri-nilkanth.html|accessdate=2016-11-10}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\n[[File:Ramanbhai Nilkanth Vidyagauri Nilkanth.jpg|thumb|Vidyagauri with her husband [[Ramanbhai Nilkanth]]|upright=0.8|left]]\nVidyagauri Nilkanth was born on 1 June 1876 in [[Ahmedabad]]. She was the daughter of a judicial officer, Gopilal Dhruva and Balaben.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://gujaratisahityaparishad.com/prakashan/sarjako/savishesh/Savishesh-Vidyagauri-Nilkanth.html|title=\u0ab5\u0abf\u0aa6\u0acd\u0aaf\u0abe\u0a97\u0acc\u0ab0\u0ac0 \u0aa8\u0ac0\u0ab2\u0a95\u0a82\u0aa0|last=Bhatt|first=Pushpa|website=gujaratisahityaparishad.com|publisher=[[Gujarati Sahitya Parishad]]|language=gu|trans-title=Vidyagauri Nilkanth|access-date=2019-01-21}}</ref><ref name=\"Stree Shakti\"/> She was a granddaughter of [[Bholanath Divetia]], a social reformer and poet.<ref name=\":2\">{{cite journal|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DeaVBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA17|title=International Journal of Afro-Asian Studies|last=Sujata|first=Menon|publisher=Universal-Publishers|year=2013|isbn=978-1-61233-709-8|editor-last=Sark